  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Also known as drug-induced hyperthermia\nAn adverse reaction to a drug in which the recipient of the drug develops a fever\nMost common drug classes are antimicrobials, anticonvulsants, antidysrhythmics, and other cardiac agents\n[1]",
      "subsections": {
        "Pathophysiology": {
          "text": "Possible mechanisms:\nHyper-metabolic state\nDirect tissue damage and tissue necrosis\nInterference with peripheral vasodilation\nActivation of the cellular or humoral immune responses\nActing as an endogenous pyrogen.",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Pathophysiology": {
      "text": "Possible mechanisms:\nHyper-metabolic state\nDirect tissue damage and tissue necrosis\nInterference with peripheral vasodilation\nActivation of the cellular or humoral immune responses\nActing as an endogenous pyrogen.",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Can occur at any point during therapy but most often occurs 7-10 days after initiation of drug\n[2]\nMay appear \"inappropriately well\" for the degree of fever",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
